<h1 class="title toc-ignore">contourr</h1>



<div id="the-virtual-snow-stake" class="section level1">
<h1>The Virtual Snow Stake</h1>
<p>The <strong>contourr</strong> package provides a simple method for extracting the outlines of an object of interest in one image and overlaying the same outlines onto new images. This vignette is a step-by-step decription of the methodology.</p>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
<p><br></p>
<div id="methodology" class="section level2">
<h2>Methodology</h2>
<p><br></p>
<p>This code uses the package <strong>imager</strong>, which is one of few image processing packages in R. This particular package has some handy built-in functions that we will be using to save a little time and computing power.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Let’s take a look at an image using <strong>imager</strong>’s “load.image” function.</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb1"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb1-1"><a href="#cb1-1"></a>im1 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">load.image</span>(<span class="st">&quot;../images/image01.jpg&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb1-2"><a href="#cb1-2"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im1)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>A color image is the combined result of three layers of pixels, one layer each for red, green, and blue shades, which are plotted below for reference. R “plots” an image by assigning a combination of red, green, and blue values to each pixel coordinate, with indexing starting in the upper left-hand corner. This image is 384 pixels wide and 256 pixels high.</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb2"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb2-1"><a href="#cb2-1"></a>red &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>im1</span>
<span id="cb2-2"><a href="#cb2-2"></a>red[,,,<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">2</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">3</span>)] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb2-3"><a href="#cb2-3"></a></span>
<span id="cb2-4"><a href="#cb2-4"></a>green &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>im1</span>
<span id="cb2-5"><a href="#cb2-5"></a>green[,,,<span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>)] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb2-6"><a href="#cb2-6"></a></span>
<span id="cb2-7"><a href="#cb2-7"></a>blue &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>im1</span>
<span id="cb2-8"><a href="#cb2-8"></a>blue[,,,<span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="dv">2</span>] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb2-9"><a href="#cb2-9"></a></span>
<span id="cb2-10"><a href="#cb2-10"></a><span class="kw">par</span>(<span class="dt">mfrow =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>), <span class="dt">mar =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>))</span>
<span id="cb2-11"><a href="#cb2-11"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(red, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span>
<span id="cb2-12"><a href="#cb2-12"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(green, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span>
<span id="cb2-13"><a href="#cb2-13"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(blue, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --> <br></p>
<p>Color images can be converted to grayscale. There are about a million ways to convert a color image to grayscale, but <strong>imager</strong> converts the luminance (brightness) of a pixel into a shade of gray. Let’s see what that looks like for our image:</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb3"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb3-1"><a href="#cb3-1"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(<span class="kw">grayscale</span>(im1), <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Now we have a black and white version of our image. This is the image from which we will extract contours.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>A contour is just an edge in an image; the “imgradient” function in <strong>imager</strong> compares the value of one pixel to the values of the pixels immediately around it. Greater differences between neighboring pixels will give a pixel a larger contour value, while weaker differences will give a smaller contour value. Images have x contours and y contours, which look like this:</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb4"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb4-1"><a href="#cb4-1"></a><span class="kw">par</span>(<span class="dt">mar =</span> <span class="kw">c</span>(.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>,.<span class="dv">1</span>))</span>
<span id="cb4-2"><a href="#cb4-2"></a>im1xy &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">imgradient</span>(<span class="kw">grayscale</span>(im1), <span class="st">&quot;xy&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb4-3"><a href="#cb4-3"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im1xy, <span class="dt">layout =</span> <span class="st">&quot;row&quot;</span>, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Next, we’ll find the distance between the values in the x contour plot and the values in the y contour plot at each pixel coordinate. When either x or y are a contour, there is a greater distance between the two values. Normalizing these distances lets us give greater weight to places in the image where there are contours. <strong>imager</strong> has a function called “enorm” which does these calculations for us. When we find the distances between the pixels in the x and y contour plots, the result is a single image which looks like this:</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb5"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb5-1"><a href="#cb5-1"></a>im1gr &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">enorm</span>(<span class="kw">imgradient</span>(<span class="kw">grayscale</span>(im1),<span class="st">&quot;xy&quot;</span>))</span>
<span id="cb5-2"><a href="#cb5-2"></a>im1cont &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">as.data.frame</span>(im1gr)</span>
<span id="cb5-3"><a href="#cb5-3"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im1gr, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --> <br></p>
<p>This is the image upon which this methodology stands. Love it, respect it, cherish it. Also, save it as a data frame, because we’ll need it later.</p>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="define-a-region-of-interest" class="section level2">
<h2>Define a Region of Interest</h2>
<p><br></p>
<p>We don’t necessarily want to find <em>every</em> contour in an image; in my case, I only want the contours of the measuring stake. Fortunately, <strong>imager</strong> has functions that allow you to output the coordinates of particular points, lines, or rectangles that you draw on an image. This lets us limit our search for contours to just a region we care about.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>The package will allow you to draw your own region using the “grabRect” function. I define my region of interest:</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb6"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb6-1"><a href="#cb6-1"></a><span class="co">#imc &lt;- grabRect(im1, output = &quot;coord&quot;) # draw a box around the object of interest</span></span>
<span id="cb6-2"><a href="#cb6-2"></a>imc &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">187</span>,<span class="dv">30</span>,<span class="dv">202</span>,<span class="dv">229</span>)</span>
<span id="cb6-3"><a href="#cb6-3"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im1, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span>
<span id="cb6-4"><a href="#cb6-4"></a><span class="kw">rect</span>(imc[<span class="dv">1</span>], imc[<span class="dv">2</span>], imc[<span class="dv">3</span>], imc[<span class="dv">4</span>], <span class="dt">border =</span> <span class="st">&quot;red&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Later, we will want to know which particular pixels in the region are the contours, so we’ll create variables to store that information.</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb7"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb7-1"><a href="#cb7-1"></a>maskx &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="ot">NULL</span></span>
<span id="cb7-2"><a href="#cb7-2"></a>masky &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="ot">NULL</span></span></code></pre></div>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="highlight-the-contours-in-an-image" class="section level2">
<h2>Highlight the Contours in An Image</h2>
<p><br></p>
<p>This next code chunk will find the coordinates of the contours in the contour image and recolor them in the original image. I went with red, but you can pick any color you like by entering new RGB values on a scale from 0-1 (red, for instance, is [1,0,0]). You must specify some contour value as the minimum threshold to keep. By trial and error, I found that 0.1 was a good threshold for this image.</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb8"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb8-1"><a href="#cb8-1"></a>imnew &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>im1</span>
<span id="cb8-2"><a href="#cb8-2"></a></span>
<span id="cb8-3"><a href="#cb8-3"></a><span class="cf">for</span> (x <span class="cf">in</span> imc[<span class="dv">1</span>]<span class="op">:</span>imc[<span class="dv">3</span>]){ <span class="co"># within the box drawn before...</span></span>
<span id="cb8-4"><a href="#cb8-4"></a>  <span class="cf">for</span> (y <span class="cf">in</span> imc[<span class="dv">2</span>]<span class="op">:</span>imc[<span class="dv">4</span>]){</span>
<span id="cb8-5"><a href="#cb8-5"></a>    pix &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">data.frame</span>(im1cont[<span class="kw">which</span>(im1cont<span class="op">$</span>x <span class="op">==</span><span class="st"> </span>x <span class="op">&amp;</span><span class="st"> </span>im1cont<span class="op">$</span>y <span class="op">==</span><span class="st"> </span>y),])</span>
<span id="cb8-6"><a href="#cb8-6"></a>    <span class="cf">if</span> (pix<span class="op">$</span>value <span class="op">&gt;</span><span class="st"> </span><span class="fl">.1</span>) { <span class="co"># if the pixel is a contour... </span></span>
<span id="cb8-7"><a href="#cb8-7"></a>      imnew[x,y,<span class="dv">1</span>,] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>) <span class="co"># change the pixel color to red</span></span>
<span id="cb8-8"><a href="#cb8-8"></a>      maskx &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">append</span>(maskx, x) </span>
<span id="cb8-9"><a href="#cb8-9"></a>      masky &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">append</span>(masky, y) <span class="co"># and save the coordinates of that pixel</span></span>
<span id="cb8-10"><a href="#cb8-10"></a>  } <span class="cf">else</span> {</span>
<span id="cb8-11"><a href="#cb8-11"></a>      imnew[x,y,<span class="dv">1</span>,] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span>im1[x,y,<span class="dv">1</span>,] <span class="co"># or else keep it the original color</span></span>
<span id="cb8-12"><a href="#cb8-12"></a>      }</span>
<span id="cb8-13"><a href="#cb8-13"></a>    }</span>
<span id="cb8-14"><a href="#cb8-14"></a>}</span></code></pre></div>
<p><br></p>
<p>What’s the result?</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb9"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb9-1"><a href="#cb9-1"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(imnew, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Now we have the original image with the contours of the snowstake highlighted. We also know the coordinates of those pixels. But this itself is not that useful; we already know where the stake is in this photo. Let’s apply this to a new photo.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>We’ll load in a second image:</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb10"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb10-1"><a href="#cb10-1"></a>im2 &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">load.image</span>(<span class="st">&quot;../images/image02.jpg&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb10-2"><a href="#cb10-2"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im2, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Then we’ll ask R to find the pixel coordinates in the second photo and change them to red as well.</p>
<p><br></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb11"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb11-1"><a href="#cb11-1"></a>  <span class="cf">for</span> (j <span class="cf">in</span> <span class="dv">1</span><span class="op">:</span><span class="kw">length</span>(maskx)){</span>
<span id="cb11-2"><a href="#cb11-2"></a>        im2[maskx[j], masky[j],<span class="dv">1</span>,] &lt;-<span class="st"> </span><span class="kw">c</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb11-3"><a href="#cb11-3"></a>  }</span>
<span id="cb11-4"><a href="#cb11-4"></a><span class="kw">plot</span>(im2, <span class="dt">axes =</span> F)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Hooray! We’ve successfully found the stake in one image and overlaid it onto a new image. Notice that the stake is now inside the door rather than on the floor. All the code does is remember the contour coordinates from the reference image and recolor them in the new image. It’s not smart enough (yet) to adjust the location of the stake if the camera viewshed changes.</p>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="caveats" class="section level2">
<h2>Caveats</h2>
<p><br></p>
<p>Here’s one more example image:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>We know that the stake is here:</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>However, since the photo is overexposed, the edges of the stake are blurred and a lot of the contours are lost.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>When you run the contourfinder function on this image, this is the result:</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," /><!-- --></p>
<p><br></p>
<p>If I didn’t have those strips of bright tape at the 10 cm marks, then my stake would be completely useless. So it is important than you have at least one good image of the reference object in order for <strong>contourr</strong> to be useful.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Vegetation, camera movement, and camera tilting are also likely issues, and I will develop more functions to deal with these issues.</p>
<p><br></p>
<hr />
<p><br></p>
</div>
<div id="other-applications" class="section level2">
<h2>Other Applications</h2>
<p><br></p>
<p>This package, or at least this methodology, will likely be useful for many camera applications which require some reference object. For instance, someone who was interested in being able to measure how far away animals are from cameras might be able to overlay a grid onto images. Or, someone who was interested in measuring the animals themselves might be able to use a similar method to mine, given that they know where the measurements will be valid (e.g. we can accurately measure a fisher that is within a meter of this particular tree, but if it is more than a meter from this tree, the measurement may not be valid).</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Happy overlaying!</p>
<p><br></p>
</div>
</div>
